summary:
The critical turn has brought a healthy, if unresolved, concern to doing ethnographic research in (forever in lieu of a better term) the “Global South”, where the South is understood as a “post-colonial context”. Broadly this comes out of both an acute awareness of geography’s ‘past littered with the skeletons of murderous neglects and encounter’ (Robinson 2003, 277) and postcolonial/feminist perspectives on the situatedness of knowledge and the concomitant relational nature of researcher positionality (England 1994; Rose 1997). At the intersection of these literatures, in the post-colonial context, the “skeletons” of the past bear on considerations of positionality where our contemporary privilege derives from and replicates – or may replicate - colonial-era power relations between researchers and Southern Others (Valentine 2005; Sidaway 2000; Skelton 2001). This work has done much for the ambitious and ongoing project towards a de- or postcolonial praxis for geography and no geographer should travel South without careful deliberation of what it means to be a “privileged western researcher” in a post-colonial field.

Still, with our privilege, “we” go. In this session we seek papers that present radical challenges to privilege and presence in the North-South encounter. We envisage contributions that fall into one of two broad themes: first, challenges to the “we” and the presumed privilege held by geographers; second, serious consideration of whether we should continue be (t)here at all, and how a radically different presence or absence might appear in practice. Within these broad themes we encourage contributions from a variety of perspectives and disciplines, from theory, methodology and/or empirical research. We invite authors to propose presentations on the following topics (this is not an exhaustive list):

“Western privilege” in the context of ethnicity, class, gender;
Embodied inter-subjectivity in research encounters;
Class and colonial histories;
Institutional prestige, mobilities, constraints;
Institutions and ethics (RECs IRBs);
Speaking to “Others”, writing about “Others” and designating “Otherness”;
Northern post-coloniality, Northern Otherness, being inbetween;
Discomfort/failure in the field;
Northern post-coloniality;
Challenges to binary presentations of Other/Self; mobility and diaspora identities.
